spanGrp.span: My grandmother came from Valle de la Estrella;
Yís mamita betẽũ rö (_) Valle de la Estrella
Valle de la Estrella is located in Talamanca;
My great-grandmother’s name is Grandma Dominga;
yís bisabwela je kie Mamita Dominga
my grandma’s name is Maria Josefa Obando.
yís mamita kie Maria Josefa Obando
She came from there, from Valle de la Estrella, from a place called Talamanca.
je betẽũ rö jega Valle de la Estrella jamĩ kã' Talamanka
And my grandpa’s name is Rafael Fernandez.
Jemẽ (_) (_) yís tatiga kie rö Rafael Fernandes
They came from that area too, from a place called San Jose Cabecar.
je betẽũ rö jamĩ je wa bö jie-wa betẽũ (_) sa kã' juei wa kã' kie San José Kabékar
Je wa yís mamita deũ rö
and so they left their homeland, came out of the mountains [and made it down here].
(_) (extra) (_) (_) Je wa jie-wa desãũ-lo rö kã'bata jãrga jie-wa desãũ-lo rö kã'bata jãrga
There is a road in the mountains, used by the ancestors long ago.
Je wa ñala kablali jenẽ rö sigeglö-wa shkö-glö rö Jenẽ rö sigeglö-wa shkö-glö rö ñã'_jiñãra kã'bata nã
Then we thus grew up around here; we are their grandchildren and we speak our language.
Jemẽra nẽ nã jera jebi sa kibinã' jiwa Sa rö í tachi-wa Sa sa tö'-gẽ se ktö'ë jemẽ jie-wa deũ-lo-te je wa
We work here and we grew up here in Ujarraz.
Sa shkablö-gẽ jiska sa kebir-gẽ rö jiska Ujarras
We all belong to the same clan.
sa rö ditsö'-wa sa rö mismo
Most of our relatives live there, in Talamanca;
Sa yaiwa kebiye tsõ rö je wa jamĩ Talamanka (_) Je wa
they are there and we are here.
jie-wa tsõ jiwa sa tsõ jebi sa damĩũ-lo pe shanã
We all work and grew up;
our great-grandparents, our children in law, our parents in law, and our grandchildren are many, not a few.
Jebi sa yaiwa rö tãĩ Sa sa (r) sa kla-wa sa döbö-wa sa nwagi-wa sa tachi-wa je rö tãĩ Ka rö jũãjũãnãgla unã
Je të kã' je köũ rö kã' klabe köũ
We do not lose our Sök language;
Ka sa të Sök ktö' she-wẽ ta (m)
we always speak it.We will never lose it.
(_) sa tö'-gẽ (_) rö (m) Ka sa wã je shewã-nã ta nunka unã
My father weaves baskets and calabashes very well.
S-kaga të jaba yue kokõblö yue tara bá köũ
My mother is ill now, but she used to prepare chicha and the porridge very well.
Yís mina döwörawã jira (_) mama të bá (_) di ble di ble bokor bi-gẽ jirö wẽ-gẽ köũ barama
We will not forget our language;
Ka sa shenã ka sa ĩã sök ktö' she-nã
we will maintain it till we die.
sa jẽr nã nunka asta sa dua-wã jenẽ kea sa të sök ktö' shewẽ-wã (r) shewẽ-wã
We are not going to lose it just like that.
There used to be a lot of thing to eat in the mountains, but not anymore.
Ñã_jiñã sigeglö/ jiskara tãĩ jirö tsõ tãĩ kã'bata nã (_) kata-nã bi jira ka je ta ĩã
Nowadays the place looks very different.
The river flooded our entire place;
jirda diglö (r) diglö wã kã' menetsẽ-mĩ kable
the whites change the course of the road.
Ka sa je/ñala (_) yua-nẽ jaule yugösuwa të
Now there are lots of whites around here.
Jirda yugösuwa ebö ñã patká tãĩ
in our language we call them Spanish;
(_) Se je ktö' wa se je të í kie rö sikwa
jie-wa/ sigeglö-wa të í (_) kie rö yugösuwa
That’s how you say it in our language.
jebi se je ktö wa í kie rö
They have many tractors, but we don’t.
Pero (_) jie-wa tsõ tãĩ tebeli_yaga ta jirö ta Ka sa je wã í ta
Long ago we used to live differently;
Ñãjĩñãra se je ser-gẽ rö jaule
They were of wood and palm leaves.
se je jũ rö kal se jũ rö sökkö' ulukö'
Now people have made nice houses with many other materials and stuff.
jira pe të se je ĩã jũ yuá-nẽ bá nẽ tebeli_yaga ebö nẽ jirö ebö nẽ
